text:
📖memória // nascida em munique, em 12 de fevereiro de 1908 e de origem judaica, olga gutmann benário prestes faria 111 anos hoje. a militante ganhou visibilidade ainda adolescente no movimento comunista alemão e foi enviada ao brasil em 1934 para apoiar o partido comunista brasileiro. junto do brasileiro luís carlos prestes, que se tornou seu marido, ela organizou a intentona comunista. após o fracasso da revolução, olga foi  deportada pelo governo vargas para a alemanha nazista em 1936, já grávida de anita, sua filha com prestes. presa, olga ficou com sua filha até o fim do período de amamentação e foi executada em 23 de abril de 1942, aos  34 anos, numa câmara de gás em bernburg, com mais 199 prisioneiras.
.
.
no brasil, um filme sobre a vida de olga foi lançado em 2004, dirigido por jayme monjardim e protagonizado por camila morgado. para lembrar hoje.

text:
women are intuitive. women possess within them, all that is needed to acknowledge and bring forth life. often, a woman knows truth even before it comes forth.
.

these intuitive traits are not just for the purpose of child bearing, they also lead women to sense truth that hides between the lines, the truth that is concealed.
.

continue to practice these tools of wisdom and discernment within the houses you stand. be the one who is paying attention- not just to that which is seen, but also to that which is unseen.

text:
farmers and shepherds on the italian island of sardinia have been pouring their milk away, saying they would rather destroy it than sell it for next to nothing.
the price of sheep milk has dropped more than 25 per cent to 60 cents a litre following a fall in the price of pecorino romano cheese, which absorbs about half the island’s sheep milk production. (euronews.com) rp @donnamaria1961 @light.knowledge.power could this be the beginning of the end?
italian farmers dump milk in protest against low prices.
could this be the impact of the rise of veganism and great demand for vegan milk, cheese etc? 
could this be the beginning of the end of the dairy industry in the eu? let's wait and see.

text: anxiety is a part of my life. i dealt with sexual and emotional abuse , neglect, suicide and the loss of my biological parents all before the age of 9. with this i’ve also dealt with the symptoms of ptsd my whole life (anxiety and depression being the hardest to deal with). having gone through every coping method possible both harmful and helpful has made me the strong woman i am today. being anxious or being aware has made me more emotionally empathetic to others around me  and to the world at large. it has also allowed me to create boundaries  from others who are toxic. my circle is very small and that’s okay. my anxiety and what i’ve been through is a form of empowerment a symbol of healing. when my anxiety is high it means i need to give a little more care to myself. it is a life long reminder that self love is not selfish. it had made me a better friend, a better wife , mother ,daughter, and overall human being. to feel everything all the time is a gift. a gift that some will never get to experience. i see , feel, love and live with all of my senses. it’s beyond intense but it’s real and it’s okay to feel.  not to over simplify and say that i don’t struggle because i do. sometimes it’s daily -but i fight through it. i’ve been through too much to quit. i move my body, i give my kids a hug and kiss, i talk to my husband, my friends  or i journal. the point is we all have our own story. our own struggles and scars  that has made us who we are. don’t cower away and live in fear of your truth . don’t stay the victim no matter how much you have been through. allow yourself to feel your pain. recover. it’s a lifelong process . speak your truth. be proud of those beautiful scars. the world needs more sincerity and more people to open up. life is all about your perspective. we can choose to be victims or we can choose to be warriors. i am a warrior. what about you?
name: Joline
tweet_full: anxiety is a part of my life. i dealt with sexual and emotional abuse , neglect, suicide and the loss of my biological parents all before the age of 9. with this i’ve also dealt with the symptoms of ptsd my whole life (anxiety and depression being the hardest to deal with). having gone through every coping method possible both harmful and helpful has made me the strong woman i am today. being anxious or being aware has made me more emotionally empathetic to others around me  and to the world at large. it has also allowed me to create boundaries  from others who are toxic. my circle is very small and that’s okay. my anxiety and what i’ve been through is a form of empowerment a symbol of healing. when my anxiety is high it means i need to give a little more care to myself. it is a life long reminder that self love is not selfish. it had made me a better friend, a better wife , mother ,daughter, and overall human being. to feel everything all the time is a gift. a gift that some will never get to experience. i see , feel, love and live with all of my senses. it’s beyond intense but it’s real and it’s okay to feel.  not to over simplify and say that i don’t struggle because i do. sometimes it’s daily -but i fight through it. i’ve been through too much to quit. i move my body, i give my kids a hug and kiss, i talk to my husband, my friends  or i journal. the point is we all have our own story. our own struggles and scars  that has made us who we are. don’t cower away and live in fear of your truth . don’t stay the victim no matter how much you have been through. allow yourself to feel your pain. recover. it’s a lifelong process . speak your truth. be proud of those beautiful scars. the world needs more sincerity and more people to open up. life is all about your perspective. we can choose to be victims or we can choose to be warriors. i am a warrior. what about you?

text:
ochre ribbon week occurs annually between 12th - 19th february. the ochre ribbon campaign is an initiative supported by the national family violence prevention legal services forum and its member organisations across australia. the ochre ribbon campaign raises awareness of the devastating impacts of family violence in aboriginal and torres strait islander communities and calls for action to end the violence against aboriginal and torres strait islander people – especially our women and children. 
violence against aboriginal and torres strait islander women devastates communities and destroys families. in comparison with other women, aboriginal and torres strait islander women are 32 times more likely to be hospitalised from family violence and 10 times more likely to be killed as a result of violent assault.

text: today is february 12. what’s significant about this date? it’s ilhan omar’s anniversary with her brother. on 2/12/2009, ilhan omar married her biological brother so that he could get a green card. she committed immigration fraud. i was the only journalist who seemed to really care about this when she was running for office and so i confronted her about this in august 2018 on video at one of her joint campaign events with rashida tlaib. i asked her “ilhan, why did you marry your brother?” the media ignored me and called me a nazi in the local paper. i was defamed for reporting the truth. i was called a racist for being the only person with balls big enough to confront theses jihadi candidates about their jew hatred and ties to terror orgs. i sent this video to @foxnews and they ignored it. now everyone is posting about ilhan omar acting like this is new information and that i never made this video. i was banned from twitter for exposing this. i was banned for posting facts that now even democrats agree with. meanwhile, ilhan is in congress and i have been smeared and de platformed. so next time you see someone talk shit about me while they act like this is their story, you let them know laura loomer did that. you let them know, because they want to erase me from the internet so that people think i don’t exist. #loomered #stopthebias #nosharia #shemarriedherbrother

text:
i hear this again and again from men struggling to meet women: .
everything is just fine until i get up in my head trying to figure out what the “right thing to say” is. then i start stumbling over my words and the energy of the interaction shifts. .
brother, you don’t have to be clever. you don’t have to pretend to have it all together. you don’t have to have any “lines” handy. you just need to be present. .
take a breath into your body and the excitement and nervousness swimming there. let go of any attachments to “getting her number” or “being impressive.” just be you. .
i remember connecting with a woman once and i said, “wow. i find you so attractive that i’m nervous even talking to you.” we both laughed, and it cleared and clarified the tension. i was congruent with myself. she though it was sweet and kinda hot. .
hiding my true experience just isn’t an option for me anymore. and loving life out loud is not only way more fun for me, but happens to be magnetic and juicy for the women i want to be connecting with. 🔥
.
bit.ly/authenticdatingsecrets
.

text:
a police charity group is backtracking from inviting former fox news anchor bill o’reilly to speak at its monthly fundraiser in new york, after the event drew backlash from the #metoo crowd, the new york times reports.

o’reilly was kicked out of fox news in 2017 over allegations of sexual harassment, ahead of the #metoo movement that would soon engulf the entertainment industry. his recent invitation by the police athletic league, initially meant to raise money, instead preceded the resignation of a board member, outrage from the national organization for women, questions from reporters, and finally, the group withdrawing from the fundraiser monday evening.  two expected attendees, the police commissioner and the manhattan district attorney, had also said they weren’t going to attend the event, and a second board member resigned, but none said it was because of o’reilly’s speech. “we want speakers to bring light and good will to p.a.l.,” said p.a.l. executive director frederick j. watts. “this speaker was distracting and it seemed inconsistent with that goal. it’s not much more complicated that.” the p.a.l., working together with the new york city police department, provides educational and recreational after school activities for children and adolescents. in the past, o’reilly has said the organization is “dear” to him. but #metoo critics say his presence at the police luncheon would do the exact opposite of what the organization was meant to promote. “it’s grotesque,” now president and commission for gender equity commissioner sonia ossorio told the new york times. “of course as a role model for positive manhood, few could fail the test as clearly as bill o’reilly.”

text:
have you witnessed or experienced obstetric violence?
.
i’ve witnessed it many times.
.
the subtle manipulations, degrading comments, crude and vulgar touching of a woman’s vagina & body... that lead to horrendous outcomes.
.
just last week the delivering ob called my clients baby a little shit for not cooperating and being delivered already (mom and baby were progressing normally) & everyone sat quiet.
.
sometimes the shock of what we witness as doulas & experience as women shuts our voices down.
.
as hard as it is, it’s important that we learn to speak up. i am committed to this now more than ever.
.
@birthmonopoly is offering a way for mothers and birth professionals to share their stories.
.
as a reminder to us all: tolerance of the subtle behaviors excuses the severe.
.
our voices are needed.
.
#doularise
.
.

text:
#metoo
vågar tillbaka.
in i rummen där minnena kan komma åt. undvikit en massa år.

han såg dig och du såg att han såg dig på svenska kyrkans ungdomsgård. bara barnet, han alldeles för vuxen, det kunde int du veta då.

varje helg tills du var femton år. sen våga han ta hem dig.

nu är du tjugotvå. det är mässa med ungdomskör och du ville testa.

alltid gått förbi. skygglapparna. nu bussen dit och stega rakt in. efter att ha smugit runt församlingsgården och spejat. nästan likadant.

nästan lika, nästan igår.

det får komma.
det går att minnas nu. 
det går att läka såpass att en står ut.

text:
sydney (austrália) — na luz suave da tarde, homens e mulheres se dividem em grupos, suas imagens refletidas em espelhos que vão do chão ao teto. alguns se beijam, acariciam uns aos outros. outros tocam as pontas dos dedos do próximo. não se trata de uma boate ou uma orgia. os homens e mulheres são atores, e estão participando de um "workshop de intimidade", parte de uma tendência crescente de criar espaços seguros nas indústrias teatral e cinematográfica.
no comando está ita o'brien, uma “coordenadora de intimidade”. ex-dançarina e diretora, ela — junto com outros “coordenadores” e dublês especializados — vem ganhando espaço numa indústria que lida com as consequências do movimento #metoo.
a londrina o'brien, de 53 anos, já prestou seus serviços para empresas como hbo e netflix. e sua abordagem, cada vez mais demandada em todo o mundo, encontrou uma ressonância particular na austrália, onde o sexismo persiste numa cena cultural que tende a ser insular — e foi recentemente criticada por proteger o status quo.
acusações de conduta sexual imprópria agitaram a indústria na austrália. a principal delas, contra o ator vencedor do oscar geoffrey rush — primeiro pela atriz eryn jean norvill, que o acusou de deliberadamente acariciar seu seio durante a produção da peça "rei lear" há três anos, e depois pela estrela da série "orange is the new black" yael stone.
no entanto, o movimento #metoo demorou a ganhar força por lá, em grande parte porque as leis de difamação do país favorecem fortemente o acusado.
leia mais neste post.
fonte: o globo

text: when girls run the world! at grammys 2019 some of music’s best names came together to honor music’s biggest hair. artists @katyperry @mileycyrus and more took on the timeless hits of @dollyparton at the 61st annual grammy awards in a performance honouring the queen of country music. @michelleobama appearance was another amazing highlight of the grammys in support of her girl alicia keys and music . 5 sterne - noch bestechender als der vorgänger
6. februar 2019
format: taschenbuch

während der leser im ersten band ‚abgründe‘ miterleben musste, wie die junge nina gegen ihren willen zur prostituierten gemacht wird, wirft dieser band ‚obsession‘ einen genaueren blick auf ninas umfeld, insbesondere auf die psyche ihres neuen freundes. scheint es auf den ersten blick so, als habe sie in nico endlich einen soliden partner gefunden, der ihr dabei helfen könnte, die szene zu verlassen, so kehren sich die rollen schon allzu bald um. will nico zunächst absolut kein geld von nina haben, so treibt er sich schon bald selbst in die finanzielle abhängigkeit; er betrügt sie, er fängt an, sie zu prügeln, wenn sie nicht genug geld bringt – kurz, er wird zu ihrem neuen zuhälter.
diese wahre geschichte zeigt auf allzu reale art, wie die rotlicht-szene ihre bewohnner an sich kettet, wie geld korrumpieren kann und wie selbst der netteste kerl von nebenan sich von dem goldenen glanz eines feuerzeugs blenden lassen kann.

text:
tarana burke is a civil rights activist and founder of the #metoo movement.
✨
burke's role as the senior director at @ggenyc in brooklyn, ny, an intergenerational nonprofit dedicated to strengthening local communities by creating opportunities for young women and girls to live self-determined lives, is a continuation of what she considers her life's work. since #metoo, the movement she created more than ten years ago, became a viral hashtag, she has emerged as a global leader in the evolving conversation around sexual violence and the need for survivor-centered solutions. her theory of using empathy to empower survivors is changing the way the nation and the world think about and engage with survivors. her belief that healing isn't a destination but a journey has touched and inspired millions of survivors who previously lived with the pain, shame and trauma of their assaults in isolation." - @ted

text:
we used to think that narratives like harassment and teasing girls, it was all acceptable and that there’s nothing wrong with it. but now, these things are gaining more definition, and are being debated over,” madam mahtab rashdi said. "things like these have urged organisations, to create a separate department to cater to issues regarding #harassment, and to take it seriously, and to protect the identity of the victim,” she said. “the point is to understand that these issues exist in every society. and they prevail because women are not taken seriously, and people get a free pass to exploit them wherever they feel the need to,” she added. in session redefining consent moderated by aisha gazdar 〰️

text: i had my makeup done by lynne spears this weekend. it was fun. i don’t think i would do well with fame. i used to want it when i was little but now i see it as a gilded cage. lynne was very gracious. she didn’t comment on my vaginas united t-shirt lol. i think it was a bit shocking for her taste but that’s cool. part of my mission is to take the taboo surrounding the word and just delete it. it’s so sill. vagina is just like the word elbow or eyeball. it’s just a part. i feel like if we could as a society delete the stigma that surrounds the word, we could deleted some of the violence towards it as well. like it would take away the mysticism and secret-ness of it, not that secret-ness is a word 😂😂😂. well have a great day ya’ll and take care of yourselves. you deserve love. ❤️💜vu #ourdaughtersarewatching #yourvoicematters #metootimesup #metoo #metooisvu #timesup #believesurvivors #metoomovement #endrape #rapeculture #rapecultureiswhen #rapecultureisreal #womensmarch #believewomen #keepfighting #truth #metoostories #abuseawareness #endrapeoncampus #enoughisenough #whyididntreport #yourvoicematters #familyviolence #itsnothyourfault #womenunited #womenpower #womenempowerment #nomeansno #survivor

text: ok i need to rant! i have been seeing so many articles and comments lately about how timmy showed his “true colours” when he ignored the #metoo movement and signed on to do a film with woody allen. i honestly have seen more articles criticizing timmy then i have of allen which deeply upsets me. people need to realize that timmy is a young actor just starting out in the business and he quickly realized after signing on with allen that he made a terrible mistake. he is doing his best to make up for it by donating his entire salary earned on the film to various charities. i don’t see people criticizing selena gomez who is also in the film. or better yet, why don’t you start talking about woody allen! the man who is actually responsible and being accused of these disturbing acts! i’ve seen articles say that timmy’s fans are so blind to the fact that he is not as perfect as they think he is. well i know he is not perfect and he made a mistake and now he is trying his best to make up for it. it is nothing compared to what allen has done and by blaming timothée for signing on to the film you are only hurting him and not allen who is the guilty person in this situation! i’m sorry i know this is a lot but i just needed to rant big time! #timotheechalamet #callmebyyourname #armiehammer #elioperlman #elioandoliver

text_retweet:
posted @withrepost • @iamkayfactor the truth we all have to contribute to end violence against women and girls. 
one of the greatest injustice we can do to girls is not to educate them. when you educate girls, it brings about economic growth. 
globally, girls are twice as likely as boys never to start school, which results in lower school completion rate (world bank). we can change this figures. when we educate women and girls, we help break the cycle of poverty or still intergenerational transfer of poverty. 
my name is hammed kayode alabi and i support girls education.

thank you life after abuse foundation for the opportunity and halima layeni for championing this cause!

text:
nikola tesla, responsible, in large part, for the technology that makes our modern society possible. a lot could be said about him, however, it should be pointed out that his later life can be seen as a case of someone that developed neurosis which is almost always from exposure to toxins.
- -
this was a man so intelligent that he invented things that were absolutely new in all of human history (not built on previously known concepts) yet in his later years he was living in poverty, obsessed with pigeons, claiming astounding new inventions from time to time with no evidence...today he would have probably been diagnosed with dementia in his later years.
- -
many more examples of historical figures can be seen to have neurosis that were no doubt brought on by the toxins they worked with. henry ford is one clear example.
- -
today toxins are ubiquitous and everyone that is not incorporating detox into their life is developing neurosis, addictions, cancer, etc. much earlier in life.
- -

text:
as i’m getting close to finishing my book, “you glow, girl!”, i’m also creating a one-on-one signature coaching program called, glow your mindset. - 
things happen to us along the journey of life that shape us, good and bad.  it’s all part of our story.  we learn from every experience and it’s what we do with our learnings that matters. - 
i’ve personally faced many challenges in my life and made the decision to learn from them and grow. -
do you aspire to do something big, but just don’t know how to get there? 
do you want to be the best version of yourself but struggle with negative thoughts? -
i will help you to embrace your story through one on one communication which i feel is so important now when everything is so automated.  i believe it’s all about authenticity, vulnerability and connection. -
i’m so excited to share my tools of transformation to help shift your mindset, face your fears, build your self-worth and be the light you were meant to be!  it’s never too late to live your dream life.  xo #youglowgirl #glowyourmindset

text:
if there’s one (or more) things i’ve learned this past year it’s this:
•take chances - even if you’re skeptical
•expect more from yourself - even if your mind has convinced itself to be complacent •be open to others - even if it’s weird...those random people you met on ig/fb might just end up being good friends you talk to every single day 😉 .
.

this february bootcamp is going to be one for the books (😂see what i did there?)

text: so this is the first time i have publicly shared part of my story. today marks a year since my life was turned upside down for the final time, the final time i had to relive every detail of the events that took place and the final time that i had to prepare myself and stand in a court full of strangers in order to fight for justice, not just for myself but for all the others involved. a year ago today i was fragile and scarred by the events of the past, petrified of my every move being under scrutiny and fear that the years of fighting and battling to have our day in court would be for nothing. today marks the start of the most hellish two weeks i’ve ever endured but it also marks the first time i understood my own mental strength and capacity, it marks my part-restored faith in the justice system, it marks the beginning of the end for something i and others had to live with for most of our lives and will continue to effect us forever under the surface. i thank every juror that sat through those two weeks, heard our stories and found robert joseph guilty on 13 counts of sexual abuse and indecent assault on 3 minors under the age of 13. i will never fall victim and i am no longer afraid, as you no longer have power or control and i am more than you or this. #metoo 💙

text:
tarana burke is a civil rights activist from new york and the founder of the me too movement. 
a survivor of sexual violence, tarana's own experiences first inspired her work in the community. in 2003 burke founded "just be," a non-profit for young black girls aged 12 to 18. in 2006, burke began using the phrase "me too" to raise awareness about the pervasiveness of sexual violence in society.

me too evolved into a broader movement in 2017, when #metoo spread virally following the harvey weinstein sexual abuse allegations. burke has been named as a "silence breaker" and person of the year by time magazine, and is currently senior director at girls for gender equity in brooklyn. 
@taranajaneen is legendary. join us at the rays of hope gala on march 2nd to celebrate her work in social activism, and make a difference in the lives of women in your community.

tickets available at: https://interimplace.akaraisin.com/ipgala19

ticket sales end february 25th. purchase soon to avoid disappointment.

text:
#metoo
this caption has no correlation to the pic. i just want to speak up about a topic that is serious and there is often little to nothing done about it. sexual harassment will not stop unless you do something about it. i know that it’s scary and it hurts because you truly feel part of you was just taken from you. but you don’t know who else you’re speaking up for. be that person and speak up and stop it. it’s disgusting for a man think that since he is “above you” or has “power” they get to do whatever they can to a women. to look at a women as if we are just an object they can touch whenever/wherever they want is sick. the last thing you want to do is bottle those emotions up and try to forget about it because you won’t. 
let someone know, your sister your parents your friends, someone. you shouldn’t feel embarrassed because truth is you’re not alone.

text: for centuries now females have fought for  equality and reproductive rights. the dairy industry is a horrid representation of the sexist and uncaring human mindset, the inability to accept someone's autonomy. cows dont produce milk without an offspring, so they are strapped down and raped. their babies are taken away from them right in front of their faces to be later killed for meat. little baby cows are killed for their own milk. how fucked up is that? what if a human child was killed for its mother's milk? we have no right to force animals into these disgusting practices. we would not wish this fate on any human mother. please tell me then, how are we as women letting this happen, and, moreover, promoting this? how can we, as women, expect fair treatment if we do not provide others with such luxury? if you are one of those people who want to argue that "cows are animals, they dont care who fucks them and they dont have feelings" i can assure you as a neuroscientist that this is grossly untrue. pretty much all species know the difference between hopelessness and wanting to reproduce. pretty much every being can experiece content or fear. simply put, they know they have a choice, they know that there is a better life. they cannot state it but they do have a voice in people like me. im not telling you to cut down on milk products. im telling you to stop investing into rape and murder. #metoo #sexist #discrimination #reproductivehealth #reproductiverights #women #womensmarch #equality #freedom #rapevictim #dairyfree #dairy #cheeze #vegan #extinctionrebellion

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting, wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting, wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."
